b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p4_hess_law" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Hess\'s Law</title>\n        <objref idref="enthalpy"/>\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n\n        <p>There are two ways to determine the amount of heat involved in a chemical change: measure\n            it experimentally, or calculate it from other experimentally determined enthalpy\n            changes. Some reactions are difficult, if not impossible, to investigate and make\n            accurate measurements difficult to carry out experimentally. And even when a reaction is\n            not hard to perform or measure, it is convenient to be able to determine the heat\n            involved in a reaction without having to perform an experiment.</p>\n        <p>Hess\xe2\x80\x99s law allows us to relate the enthalpies of different reactions. </p>\n        <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"/>\n        <dl>\n            <dt><em>Hess\'s Law</em></dt>\n            <dd>\n                <p>If a process can be written as the sum of several stepwise processes, the\n                    enthalpy change of the total process equals the sum of the enthalpy changes of\n                    the various steps.</p></dd>\n        </dl>\n        <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"/>\n\n        <p> Hess\xe2\x80\x99s law is valid because enthalpy is a state function: Enthalpy changes depend only\n            on where a chemical process starts and ends, but not on the path it takes from start to\n            finish. For example, we can think of the reaction of carbon with oxygen to form carbon\n            dioxide as occurring either directly or by a two-step process. The direct process is\n            written:</p>\n        <formula>$$\\mathrm C(s)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm\n            O}_2(g)\\;\\;\\rightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm{CO}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta{H^{\\mathrm\n            o}}_{298}\\;=\\;-394\\;\\mathrm{kJ}\\;\\;$$</formula>\n\n\n        <p> We can also consider a two-step process, where first carbon monoxide is formed in the\n            first step: </p>\n        <formula>$$\\mathrm C(s)\\;+\\;{\\textstyle\\frac12}{\\mathrm\n            O}_2(g)\\;\\;\\rightarrow\\;\\;\\mathrm{CO}(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta{H^{\\mathrm\n            o}}_{298}\\;=\\;-111\\;\\mathrm{kJ}\\;\\;$$</formula>\n\n\n        <p>In the second step, carbon monoxide reacts further to form carbon dioxide: </p>\n        <formula>$$\\mathrm{CO}(g)\\;+\\;{\\textstyle\\frac12}{\\mathrm\n            O}_2(g)\\;\\;\\rightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm{CO}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta{H^{\\mathrm\n            o}}_{298}\\;=\\;-283\\;\\mathrm{kJ}\\;\\;$$</formula>\n\n\n\n        <p>The equation describing the overall reaction is the sum of these two chemical\n            changes:</p>\n        <formula>\n            <m:math display="block">\n                <m:mtable columnalign="left">\n                    <m:mtr>\n                        <m:mtd>\n                            <m:mtext>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\n                                &nbsp; Step 1: &nbsp;C(</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mi>s</m:mi>\n                            <m:mtext>) &nbsp;+ &nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mfrac>\n                                <m:mtext>1</m:mtext>\n                                <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                            </m:mfrac>\n                            <m:msub>\n                                <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                                <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                            </m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                            <m:mtext>) &nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mo lspace="3px" rspace="3px">&rarr;</m:mo>\n                            <m:mtext>&nbsp;CO(</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                            <m:mtext>)</m:mtext>\n                        </m:mtd>\n                    </m:mtr>\n                    <m:mtr>\n                        <m:mtd>\n                            <m:munder>\n                                <m:mrow>\n                                    <m:mtext>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\n                                        &nbsp; &nbsp; Step 2: &nbsp;CO(</m:mtext>\n                                    <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                                    <m:mtext>) +&nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                                    <m:mfrac>\n                                        <m:mtext>1</m:mtext>\n                                        <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                                    </m:mfrac>\n                                    <m:msub>\n                                        <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                                        <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                                    </m:msub>\n                                    <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                                    <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                                    <m:mtext>) &nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                                    <m:mo lspace="3px" rspace="3px">&rarr;</m:mo>\n                                    <m:mtext>&nbsp;C</m:mtext>\n                                    <m:msub>\n                                        <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                                        <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                                    </m:msub>\n                                    <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                                    <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                                    <m:mtext>)</m:mtext>\n                                </m:mrow>\n                                <m:mo>&macr;</m:mo>\n                            </m:munder>\n                            <m:mtext>&nbsp; &nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                        </m:mtd>\n                    </m:mtr>\n                    <m:mtr>\n                        <m:mtd>\n                            <m:mtext>Sum: C(s) &nbsp;+ &nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mfrac>\n                                <m:mtext>1</m:mtext>\n                                <m:mtext>2</m:mtext>\n                            </m:mfrac>\n                            <m:mtext>&nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                            <m:msub>\n                                <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                                <m:mtext>2</m:mtext>\n                            </m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                            <m:mtext>) &nbsp;+ &nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                            <m:menclose notation="updiagonalstrike">\n                                <m:mrow>\n                                    <m:mtext>CO(</m:mtext>\n                                    <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                                    <m:mtext>)&nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                                </m:mrow>\n                            </m:menclose>\n                            <m:mtext>&nbsp;+ &nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mfrac>\n                                <m:mtext>1</m:mtext>\n                                <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                            </m:mfrac>\n                            <m:mtext>&nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                            <m:msub>\n                                <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                                <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                            </m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                            <m:mtext>) &nbsp;\xe2\x86\x92 &nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                            <m:menclose notation="updiagonalstrike">\n                                <m:mrow>\n                                    <m:mtext>CO(</m:mtext>\n                                    <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                                    <m:mtext>)</m:mtext>\n                                </m:mrow>\n                            </m:menclose>\n                            <m:mtext>&nbsp; + &nbsp;C</m:mtext>\n                            <m:msub>\n                                <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                                <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                            </m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                            <m:mtext>)</m:mtext>\n                        </m:mtd>\n                    </m:mtr>\n                </m:mtable>\n            </m:math>\n        </formula>\n        <p>Because the CO produced in Step 1 is consumed in Step 2, the net change is:</p>\n        <formula>$$\\mathrm C(s)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm\n            O}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{CO}}_2(g)$$</formula>\n\n        <p>According to Hess\xe2\x80\x99s law, the enthalpy change of the reaction will equal the sum of the\n            enthalpy changes of the steps. Because, in this case, the first two steps are combustion\n            reactions, we can use the enthalpies of combustion found on the table on page:\n                <activity_link idref="p2_enthalpy_comb" target="new">Enthalpies of\n                Combustion</activity_link> to find the enthalpy change of the entire reaction from\n            its two steps: </p>\n        <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm C(s)\\;+\\;{\\textstyle\\frac12}{\\mathrm\n            O}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\mathrm{CO}(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n            H_{298}^{\\mathrm\n            o}\\;=\\;-111\\;\\mathrm{kJ}\\\\\\underline{\\mathrm{CO}(g)\\;+\\;{\\textstyle\\frac12}{\\mathrm\n            O}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{CO}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta H_{298}^{\\mathrm\n            o}\\;=\\;-283\\;\\mathrm{kJ}}\\\\\\mathrm C(s)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm\n            O}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{CO}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n            H_{298}^{\\mathrm o}\\;=\\;-394\\;\\mathrm{kJ}\\end{array}$$</formula>\n\n\n        <p>The result is shown in the diagram below. We see that \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em> of the\n            overall reaction is the same whether it occurs in one step or two. This finding (overall\n                \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em> for the reaction = sum of \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em>\n            values for reaction \xe2\x80\x9csteps\xe2\x80\x9d in the overall reaction) is true in general for chemical and\n            physical processes.</p>\n        <image src="../webcontent/enthalpy_hess_image.PNG"\n            alt="A diagram is shown. A long arrow faces upward on the left with the phrase \xe2\x80\x9cH increasing.\xe2\x80\x9d A horizontal line at the bottom of the diagram is shown with the formula \xe2\x80\x9cC O subscript 2 (g)\xe2\x80\x9d below it. A horizontal line at the top of the diagram has the formulas \xe2\x80\x9cC (s) + O subscript 2 (g)\xe2\x80\x9d above it. The top and bottom lines are connected by a downward facing arrow with the value \xe2\x80\x9c\xce\x94 H = \xe2\x80\x93394 k J\xe2\x80\x9d written beside it. Below and to the right of the top horizontal line is a second horizontal line with the equations \xe2\x80\x9cC O (g) + one half O subscript 2 (g)\xe2\x80\x9d above it. This line and the bottom line are connected by a downward facing arrow with the value \xe2\x80\x9c\xce\x94 H = \xe2\x80\x93283 k J\xe2\x80\x9d written beside it. The same line and the top line are connected by a downward facing arrow with the value \xe2\x80\x9c\xce\x94 H = \xe2\x80\x93111 k J\xe2\x80\x9d written beside it. There are three brackets to the right of the diagram. The first bracket runs from the top horizontal line to the second horizontal line. It is labeled, \xe2\x80\x9cEnthalpy of reactants.\xe2\x80\x9d The second bracket runs from the second horizontal line to the bottom horizontal line. It is labeled, \xe2\x80\x9cEnthalpy of products.\xe2\x80\x9d Both of these brackets are included in the third bracket which runs from the top to the bottom of the diagram. It is labeled, \xe2\x80\x9cEnthalpy change of exothermic reaction in 1 or 2 steps.\xe2\x80\x9d"\n            width="600">\n            <caption>The formation of CO<sub>2</sub>(g) from its elements can be thought of as\n                occurring in two steps, which sum to the overall reaction, as described by Hess\xe2\x80\x99s\n                law. The horizontal blue lines represent enthalpies. For an exothermic process, the\n                products are at lower enthalpy than the reactants.</caption>\n        </image>\n        <p>Before we further practice using Hess\xe2\x80\x99s law, let us recall two important features of \xce\x94<em\n                style="italic">H</em>.</p>\n        <p>\xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em> is directly proportional to the quantities of reactants or\n            products. For example, the enthalpy change for the reaction forming 1 mole of\n                NO<sub>2</sub>(g) is +33.2 kJ :</p>\n        <formula>$${\\textstyle\\frac12}{\\mathrm N}_2(g)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm\n            O}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{NO}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{\xce\x94H}=+33.2\\;\\mathrm{kJ}$$</formula>\n        <p>When 2 moles of NO<sub>2</sub> (twice as much) are formed, the \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em>\n            will be twice as large:</p>\n        <formula>$${\\mathrm N}_2(g)\\;+\\;2\\;{\\mathrm\n            O}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;2\\;{\\mathrm{NO}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n            H=+66.4\\;\\mathrm{kJ}$$</formula>\n        <p>In general, if we multiply (or divide) an equation by a number, then the enthalpy change\n            should also be multiplied (or divided) by the same number.</p>\n        <p> \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em> for a reaction in one direction is equal in magnitude and\n            opposite in sign to \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em> for the reaction in the reverse\n            direction. For example, given that: </p>\n        <formula>$${\\mathrm\n            H}_2(g)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;2\\;\\mathrm{HCl}(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n            H\\;=-184.6\\mathrm{kJ}$$</formula>\n        <p> Then, for the \xe2\x80\x9creverse\xe2\x80\x9d reaction, the enthalpy change is also \xe2\x80\x9creversed\xe2\x80\x9d: </p>\n        <formula>$$\\;2\\;\\mathrm{HCl}(g)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;\\;{\\mathrm\n            H}_2(g)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n            H\\;=+184.6\\mathrm{kJ}$$</formula>\n        <example>\n            <p>Determine the enthalpy of formation, \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em><sub>f</sub> of\n                    FeCl<sub>3</sub>(s) from the enthalpy changes of the following two-step process\n                that occurs under standard state conditions:</p>\n            <formula>\n                $$\\begin{array}{l}\\;\\mathrm{Fe}(s)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{FeCl}}_2(s)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n                H^\\circ\\;=\\;-341.8\\mathrm{kJ}\\;\\;\\\\{\\mathrm{FeCl}}_2(s)\\;+\\;{\\textstyle\\frac12}\\;{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{FeCl}}_3(s)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n                H^\\circ\\;=\\;-57.7\\mathrm{kJ}\\;\\;\\\\\\end{array}$$ </formula>\n            <p> We are trying to find the standard enthalpy of formation of FeCl<sub>3</sub>(s),\n                which is equal to \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em>\xc2\xb0 for the reaction: </p>\n            <formula>\n                $$\\begin{array}{l}\\;\\mathrm{Fe}(s)\\;+\\;{\\textstyle\\frac32}{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{FeCl}}_3(s)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n                H_f^o\\;=\\;?\\;\\;\\\\\\;\\\\\\end{array}$$ </formula>\n            <p> Looking at the reactions, we see that the reaction for which we want to find \xce\x94<em\n                    style="italic">H</em>\xc2\xb0 is the sum of the two reactions with known \xce\x94<em\n                    style="italic">H</em> values, so we must sum their \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em>s: </p>\n            <formula>\n                $$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{Fe}(s)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{FeCl}}_2(s)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n                H^\\circ\\;=\\;-341.8\\;\\mathrm{kJ}\\\\\\underline{{\\mathrm{FeCl}}_2(\\mathrm\n                s)\\;+\\;{\\textstyle\\frac12}\\;{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2(\\mathrm\n                g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{FeCl}}_3(\\mathrm\n                s)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{\xce\x94H}^\\circ\\;=\\;-57.7\\mathrm{kJ}}\\\\\\mathrm{Fe}(s)\\;+\\;{\\textstyle\\frac32}{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{FeCl}}_3(s)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n                H^\\mathrm\n                o\\;=\\;-399.5\\;\\mathrm{kJ}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\\\\\;\\\\\\end{array}$$ </formula>\n            <p>The enthalpy of formation, \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em><sub>f</sub>, of\n                    FeCl<sub>3</sub>(s) is \xe2\x88\x92399.5 kJ/mol.</p>\n        </example>\n        <wb:inline idref="hess_digt1" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n        <p>Many times the given steps do not add up to the equation in question and some\n            manipulation of the equations is required. Here we will look at some such examples.</p>\n        <example>\n            <p>Chlorine monofluoride can react with fluorine to form chlorine trifluoride:</p>\n            <formula>$$(\\mathrm i)\\;\\mathrm{ClF}(g)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm\n                F}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{ClF}}_3(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\Delta\n                H^\\circ=?$$</formula>\n            <p>Use the reactions here to determine the \xce\x94H\xc2\xb0 for reaction (i):</p>\n            <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}(ii)\\;\\;2\\;{\\mathrm{OF}}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm\n                O}_2(g)\\;+\\;2\\;{\\mathrm\n                F}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\Delta\n                H_{(ii)}^o\\;=-49.4\\;kJ\\\\(iii)\\;2\\;\\mathrm{ClF}(g)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm\n                O}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2\\mathrm\n                O(g)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm{OF}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\Delta\n                H_{(iii)}^o=+205.6\\;kJ\\\\(iv)\\;{\\mathrm{ClF}}_3(g)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm\n                O}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\textstyle\\frac12}\\;{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2\\mathrm\n                O(g)\\;+\\;{\\textstyle\\frac32}\\;{\\mathrm{OF}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\Delta\n                H_{(iv)}^o=+266.7\\;kJ\\end{array}$$</formula>\n            <p>Our goal is to manipulate and combine reactions (ii), (iii), and (iv) such that they\n                add up to reaction (i). Going from left to right in (i), we first see that ClF(g) is\n                needed as a reactant. This can be obtained by multiplying reaction (iii) by 1/2,\n                which means that the \xce\x94H\xc2\xb0 change is also multiplied by 1/2:</p>\n            <formula>$$\\mathrm{ClF}(g)\\;+\\;{\\textstyle\\frac12}\\;{\\mathrm\n                O}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\textstyle\\frac12}\\;{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2\\mathrm\n                O(g)\\;+\\;{\\textstyle\\frac12}\\;{\\mathrm{OF}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n                H^\\circ=\\;{\\textstyle\\frac12}(205.6)\\;=\\;+102.8\\;\\mathrm{kJ}$$</formula>\n            <p>Next, we see that F<sub>2</sub> is also needed as a reactant. To get this, reverse\n                and halve reaction (ii), which means that the \xce\x94H\xc2\xb0 changes sign and is halved:</p>\n            <formula>$${\\textstyle\\frac12}{\\textstyle\\;}{\\mathrm O}_2(g)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm\n                F}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{OF}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\Delta\n                H^\\circ=+24.7\\;\\mathrm{kJ}$$</formula>\n            <p>To get ClF<sub>3</sub> as a product, reverse (iv), changing the sign of \xce\x94H\xc2\xb0:</p>\n            <formula> $${\\textstyle\\frac12}{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2\\mathrm\n                O(g)\\;+\\;{\\textstyle\\frac32}{\\mathrm{OF}}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{ClF}}_3(g)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm\n                O}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\Delta H^\\circ=-266.7\\;\\mathrm{kJ}\\;$$ </formula>\n            <p>Now check to make sure that these reactions add up to the reaction we want:</p>\n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{ClF}(g)\\;+\\;\\cancel{{\\textstyle\\frac12}{\\mathrm\n                O}_2(\\mathrm g)}\\;\\longrightarrow\\cancel{\\;{\\textstyle\\frac12}{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2\\mathrm\n                O(\\mathrm g)}\\;+\\;\\cancel{{\\textstyle\\frac12}{\\mathrm{OF}}_2(\\mathrm\n                g)}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n                H^\\circ=+102.8\\mathrm{kJ}\\\\\\cancel{{\\textstyle\\frac12}\\;{\\mathrm O}_2(\\mathrm\n                g)}\\;+\\;{\\mathrm F}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\cancel{{\\mathrm{OF}}_2(\\mathrm\n                g)\\;}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n                H^\\circ=+24.7\\;\\mathrm{kJ}\\\\\\;\\underline{\\cancel{{\\textstyle\\frac12}\\;{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2\\mathrm\n                O(\\mathrm g)}\\;+\\;\\cancel{{\\textstyle\\frac32}\\;{\\mathrm{OF}}_2(\\mathrm\n                g)}\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{ClF}}_3(\\mathrm g)\\;+\\;\\cancel{{\\mathrm O}_2(\\mathrm\n                g)\\;}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{\xce\x94H}^\\circ=-266.7\\mathrm{kJ}}\\\\\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{ClF}(\\mathrm\n                g)\\;\\;+{\\mathrm F}_2(\\mathrm g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{ClF}}_3(\\mathrm\n                g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n                H^\\circ=-139.2\\;\\mathrm{kJ}\\\\\\end{array}$$</formula>\n\n        </example>\n        <section>\n            <title/>\n            <body>\n                <section>\n                    <title>Interactive Example</title>\n                    <body>\n                        <p>Use the equations below to determine \xce\x94<em style="italic"\n                                >H</em><sup>\xe2\x88\x98</sup> for the given reaction.</p>\n                        <formula>\n                            $$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{HCl}(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\mathrm{HCl}(aq)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{\xce\x94H}=-74.8\\mathrm{kJ}\\\\{\\mathrm\n                            H}_2(g)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm{Cl}}_2(g)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;2\\;\\mathrm{HCl}(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{\xce\x94H}=-185\\mathrm{kJ}\\\\{\\mathrm{AlCl}}_3(aq)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{AlCl}}_3(s)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{\xce\x94H}=+323\\mathrm{kJ}\\\\2\\;\\mathrm{Al}(s)\\;+\\;6\\;\\mathrm{HCl}(aq)\\;\\longrightarrow\\;2\\;{\\mathrm{AlCl}}_3(aq)\\;+\\;3\\;{\\mathrm\n                            H}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{\xce\x94H}=-1049\\mathrm{kJ}\\end{array}$$ </formula>\n                        <p>Press "NEXT" to advance the slides.</p>\n                        <wb:inline idref="hess_ie"/>\n\n\n\n                    </body>\n                </section>\n            </body>\n        </section>\n\n        <composite_activity purpose="learnbydoing">\n            <p>Calculate \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em><sup>o</sup> for the following reaction:\n                    <formula>$$2\\;\\mathrm C(s)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm H}_2(g)\\;\\rightarrow\\;{\\mathrm\n                    C}_2{\\mathrm H}_2(g)$$</formula>\n                <p>from the following information:</p></p>\n            <wb:inline idref="hess_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n        </composite_activity>\n        <composite_activity purpose="learnbydoing">\n            <p> Calculate \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em><sup>o</sup> for the following reaction: </p>\n            <formula> $$4\\;{\\mathrm{NH}}_3(g)\\;+\\;5\\;{\\mathrm\n                O}_2(g)\\;\\rightarrow\\;4\\;\\mathrm{NO}(g)\\;+\\;6\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm O(g)$$ </formula>\n            <p> from the following information: </p>\n            <wb:inline idref="hess_lbd2"/>\n        </composite_activity>\n        <wb:inline idref="hess_digt2" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'